String Functions

In real databases, text data is rarely clean or consistent. You will see:

Different letter cases (Apple, apple, APPLE)
Accents (café, cafe)
Extra spaces
Mixed formats

String functions help us normalize, format, and filter text data so that comparisons, searches, and reports behave correctly. But before using string functions, it is very important to understand how SQL treats strings internally.

In SQL, a string is not just characters. Every string value is stored with the actual text and collation rules that decide how text is compared, sorted, matched. That’s why two strings that look different may still be treated as equal.

| Flag | Meaning             | What it controls              | Example comparison | Result     |
|------|--------------------|------------------------------|--------------------|------------|
| ai   | Accent-Insensitive | Ignores accents (é, è, ñ)    | cafe vs café       | Equal      |
| as   | Accent-Sensitive   | Respects accents             | cafe vs café       | Not equal  |
| ci   | Case-Insensitive   | Ignores letter case          | Apple vs apple     | Equal      |
| cs   | Case-Sensitive     | Respects letter case         | Apple vs apple     | Not equal  |

CONCAT() vs CONCAT_WS()
CONCAT(a,b,c...) joins strings as-is
CONCAT_WS(sep, a,b,c...) joins strings with a separator (WS = with separator) and skips NULL values
Examples:

SELECT CONCAT('Hello', ' ', 'Raj');
Output: Hello Raj
----------------------------------------------------------------------
SELECT CONCAT('Hello', NULL, 'Raj');
Output: NULL
CONCAT() returns NULL if any argument is NULL.
----------------------------------------------------------------------
SELECT CONCAT_WS(' ', 'Hello', NULL, 'Raj');
Output: Hello Raj
CONCAT_WS() ignores NULLs.
----------------------------------------------------------------------
SELECT CONCAT_WS('. ', NULL, 'Hi', 'Raj');
Output: Hi. Raj
NULL skipped, separator applied only between real values.

Use CONCAT() when you’re sure there’s no NULL; use CONCAT_WS() when NULLs may exist.
----------------------------------------------------------------------

LOWER() / UPPER()
LOWER() converts text to lowercase
UPPER() converts text to uppercase

SELECT LOWER('RAjstriveR');
SELECT UPPER('RAjstriveR');
----------------------------------------------------------------------
TRIM() / LTRIM() / RTRIM()
TRIM() removes spaces from both sides
LTRIM() removes spaces from left only
RTRIM() removes spaces from right only

SELECT TRIM('  RAJ  ');
SELECT LTRIM(' RAJ ');
SELECT RTRIM(' RAJ ');
----------------------------------------------------------------------
LENGTH() vs CHAR_LENGTH()
LENGTH() → number of bytes
CHAR_LENGTH() → number of characters

SELECT LENGTH('RAJ'); - 3
SELECT LENGTH('é');   - 2
SELECT LENGTH('😀'); - 4 emoji is 4 length character , length calculates with bytes 

SELECT CHAR_LENGTH('RAJ'); - 3
SELECT CHAR_LENGTH('é');   - 1
SELECT CHAR_LENGTH('😀');  - 1
----------------------------------------------------------------------
 LEFT() / RIGHT() / SUBSTRING()

LEFT(str, n) = first n characters
RIGHT(str, n) = last n characters
SUBSTRING(str, start, len) = slice string

SELECT LEFT('plus_user', 3); - plu
SELECT RIGHT('plus_user', 4); - user
SELECT SUBSTRING('plus_user', 3); - us_user
SSELECT SUBSTRING('plus_user', 3, 2); - us
----------------------------------------------------------------------
LOCATE() / INSTR()
LOCATE(substr, str)
INSTR(str, substr)
1-based indexing
Returns 0 if not found

SELECT LOCATE('@', 'Raj@gmail.com'); - 4
SELECT INSTR('Raj@gmail.com', '@');  - 4
SELECT INSTR('Raj@gmail.com', '7');  - 0
----------------------------------------------------------------------
REPLACE() Replaces all occurrences of a substring. 

SELECT REPLACE('a_b_c', '_', '-');

Output: a-b-c
----------------------------------------------------------------------
LIKE Pattern Matching

Wildcards

% = any length
_ = exactly one character

SELECT 'plus_user' LIKE 'plus%'; - 'plus%' → starts with plus, anything after is allowed
SELECT 'plus1user' LIKE 'plus_us_r'; - Matches exactly 1 character (not 0, not many) first_ matches with _ and second matches with e only one character

escape the wildcars then use SELECT 'plus1user' LIKE 'plus\_user';
Note: Escaping wildcards (\_ , \%) depends on SQL mode.
