Editing Data and Tables

Every real application needs to add new information, update existing records, and remove outdated or incorrect data. This is where SQL’s DML (Data Manipulation Language) commands come into play.

1. INSERT
INSERT is used to add new rows into a table.
INSERT INTO employees (emp_id, name, department, salary, hire_date, is_active) VALUES
(301, 'Neha Sharma',  'Sales',55000.00, '2024-03-11', TRUE);
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
UPSERT
UPSERT is a database operation that inserts a new record if it does not exist, or updates the existing record if it already exists based on a unique or primary key constraint.In simple terms, “Insert the row if it is new; otherwise, update the existing row.”
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
INSERT INTO employees (emp_id, name, department, salary, hire_date, is_active)
VALUES (301, 'Raj Sharma', 'Eng', 57000.00, '2029-01-01', TRUE)
AS new_record
ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE
  name        = new_record.name,
  department  = new_record.department,
  salary      = new_record.salary,
  hire_date   = new_record.hire_date,
  is_active   = new_record.is_active;

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
UPDATE
UPDATE changes values in existing rows.

UPDATE employees
SET department = 'HR';


This query updates every row in the table. Since no WHERE clause is used, all employees are assigned to the HR department. This is considered dangerous in production systems.
UPDATE employees
SET department = 'Eng'
WHERE employee_id = 305;

UPDATE employees
SET department = 'HR',
    salary = 65000
WHERE employee_id = 305;


UPDATE employees
SET salary = salary * 1.5
WHERE hire_date >= '2024-01-01';

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
DELETE
DELETE removes one or more rows from a table.

DELETE a Single Row

DELETE FROM employees
WHERE emp_id = 305;

DELETE FROM employees
WHERE employee_id IN (301, 302); 

DELETE FROM employees; but still row is present with empty values
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ALTER
The ALTER statement is used to modify the structure of an existing table without deleting the table or its data.

Assume below base table before ALTER operations

ALTER TABLE employees
ADD COLUMN temp_check INT;


UPDATE employees
SET temp_check = 10;

ALTER TABLE employees
RENAME TO employees_v2;

ALTER TABLE employees_v2
RENAME COLUMN temp_check TO temp_check_v2;


ALTER TABLE employees
DROP COLUMN temp_check;
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
CHANGE Clause

Renames a column and can also change its datatype and constraints at the same time.

Column name must be specified twice (old and new)
Datatype must be redefined, even if unchanged
Can modify constraints (NOT NULL, DEFAULT, etc.)

ALTER TABLE employees
CHANGE salary monthly_salary DECIMAL(10,2);
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
MODIFY Clause

Changes the datatype or constraints of a column while keeping the column name the same.

ALTER TABLE table_name
MODIFY column_name new_data_type;

ALTER TABLE table_name
MODIFY column_name new_data_type;
If you only want to change the datatype or constraints, use MODIFY. Use CHANGE only when renaming the column is explicitly required. Many production bugs happen due to accidental column renaming with CHANGE.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TRUNCATE
TRUNCATE is a Data Definition Language (DDL) operation used to remove all rows from a table quickly and efficiently.

Remove all rows from a table
Reset the table to an empty state
Perform faster than DELETE without WHERE

		DELETE				TRUNCATE			DROP
Best use-       Remove specific records		Reset / clear table quickly	Remove table permanently
